Further Examining Relevant Correlations

With the information given by FigureÂ 1, I visualized the relationship between happiness_score and 3 variables from the GDP dataset using scatterplots. These demonstrate a clearer relationship between happiness and the independent variable.

Happiness Score vs.Â GDP per Person Over Labor Force

FigureÂ 2 shows a scatterplot of happiness score vs.Â GDP per person in the labor force. Happiness Score vs.Â Employment Rate

FigureÂ 3 shows a scatterplot of happiness score vs.Â employment rate. The plot shows positive relationship between the variables: as employment rate increases, happiness score also increases.

Happiness Score vs.Â Hours Worked per Employed Person

FigureÂ 4 shows a scatterplot of happiness score vs.Â hours worked per employed person. I expected a strong, negative linear relationship between these variables, but the negative relationship between happiness score and hours worked per employed person is weak.

Density per Region

The scatterplots revealed that relationships that I believed would be strong existed, but were not as strong as I had believed. In addition, they revealed outliers that may skew the lines of best fit in adverse ways. Thus, faceting by the variable region may give further insight into certain relationships on productivity, GDP, and happiness. FigureÂ 5 shows the counts of observations in the 10 different regions that are represented in the dataset. This shows that further explorations can factor in region, because factoring by country was not possible with such few observations per level.

Happiness Score vs.Â Hours Worked per Employed Person by Region

An example of further data exploration faceted by region is a faceted scatterplot of happiness score vs.Â hours worked per employed person by region in FigureÂ 6. This reveals that the negative relationship shown in FigureÂ 4 is present and strong in Western Europe, but not so pronounced in other regions. For example, Central and Eastern European countries seem to actually have a positive relationship between happiness score and hours worked per employed person.

Conclusion

My exploration started with some data cleaning to get a dataset that I could work with. Then, I created a correlation plot to determine which relationships would be worth exploring. Scatterplots of relevant relationships further revealed that relationships that I expected to be strong were not. Finally, I factored by region to explore certain relationships further in the data exploration process.

My findings reveal that there are positive relationships between happiness score and GDP per person in the labor force and happiness score and employment rate. There is a negative relationship between happiness score and hours worked per employed person. However, this relationship only seems to be negative for countries in the Western European region.

Next Steps

Some potential next steps include fitting my scatterplots with lines that are not just linear and faceting more relationships by region.

I also want to look at more relationships between happiness score and other variables from the GDP dataset and including other relevant variables from the happiness dataset, such as generosity. However, I am unsure how to include these variables without cluttering my report with too much information without a concise goal. My exploration aims to find the balance between measures of happiness and productivity, so I need to determine exactly how to quantify productivity.

Finally, I hope to map time trends (from 2015-2019) by region to see if there are any regions seeing âimprovementsâ in various metrics over time.
